"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. One of the things that Albert Howard contributed was a method to make high-quality compost to create organic matter ready for digestion. And it was called the indoor method. And indoors in indoor India, I N-D-O-R-E, not indoor outdoor. That's a real confusing one, which he'd given it a different name. But it was a tribute to the indoor people who had helped him come up with it and worked with them and uh who he had worked with. And this method of creating high-value compost is the answer to soil banditry that the Europeans had and uh European cultures and civilizations had run into, which was that the farming method they did that was based solely on production depleted the fertility of the soil, depleted the organic matter out of the soil. And what eventually happens is that you have to replenish this with all sorts of chemical additives if you're not going to be adding the organic meth matter. Now, nature in all their its systems is constantly dropping organic matter in the form of leaves and bug carcasses and old trees and grasses and everything else onto the ground, and that gets decayed into the uh soil and digested into the soil through the decay cycle. And this is nature's method of creating more organic matter into the ground, which creates greater fertility, which can grow larger plants, and then the production value is based on a balance within the decay cycle and the growth cycle. In conventional agriculture, we abandon the decay cycle, focusing entirely on the growth cycle, and eventually the soil is depleted of its organic matter, and everything is based upon chemical additives. And when I say chemical, I don't necessarily mean things that are inorganic, but concentrates, extracts, things that aren't uh organic matter. And I think coming up with a scalable method to put more organic matter into the ground is very doable. We just need to transfer our energies from disposing of waste the way we do, and which is horrible. And a lot of times we burn it for its organic matter. We place it in a place uh a concentrated area, a landfill or something where the decay cycle is completely broken and things just sit. And what we could be doing is taking the organic material out of it, cleaning it through the composting, hot composting method, and adding it to the fields to increase fertility. This increased fertility, this biology that you're adding to the field would help with everything. It helped with the soil structure holding water, it would help with the soil uh creating a biological resistance against disease and pestilence. It would help with the fertility uh in terms of the growth of the plants, especially in terms of the inputs that are needed in today's conventional agriculture. Anyway, just wanted to make that a little video. Thanks.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.4,\n      \"end\": 1.52,\n      \"duration\": 1.12,\n      \"confidence\": 0.979,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.963\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.72,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \".\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,\n          \"end\": 1.52,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          